Conditions - 4<br />
<!--163-->Thin and Stretched x4  </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000">Strategy</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Free Peoples - <br />
<br />
Start Gandalf and bid about 2-3. If you win, go first and pull Aragorn. If you loose and they choose to play, they will either start the pony as well, or you will just have to draw him. I play 4 Barliman, because he let&#39;s you play Servant of the Secret Fire a bunch of times, and that is pretty good. I play 2 Aragorn&#39;s Bow and 2 Ranger&#39;s Versatility because they are just to good not to put in any deck that can support them. The deck can get to a point where the Versatility / archery total of 2 can be devastating, becuase even if a minion lives my guys are so massive in combonation with Servant of the Secret Fire that they rarely loose. An all around balanced deck and a break from the Arwen + Legolas start.<br />
<br />
Shadow - <br />
<br />
Play cheap Orcs and Thin and Stretched early to get burdens on Frodo. Once they hit 4 Toldea gets to pick his fights, and once they hit 5, Enquea is devastating. 12 of the Orcs have the wound me to wound you ability, and Band of the Eye is just massive. Enduring Evil is to help your non-Nazgul win fights, and in multiples can even overwhelm big guys early on, especially with Band of the Eye. The Nazgul really go well in this deck, because they give you guys to play early on, and they help against archery a great deal.<br />
<br />
Thanks for Looking,<br />
-Adam &quot;Vincent Vega&quot; Beauchamp </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000"> </Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">DeckTech <BR> For the Players, By the Players  <BR>www.decktech.net </FONT></TD></TR></table> 
